democratic presidential nominee michael 
dukakis hopes his flagging campaign gets a boost from his 
appearance on nightline tonight that goes beyond the television 
programs viewers 
dukakis trailing republican george bush in the polls with just 
two weeks until election day seems to have everything to gain from 
his appearance on the 90minute edition of the abc news program 
the interview by host ted koppel will be conducted facetoface 
a format the massachusetts governor insisted on 
for the governor its more natural than staring into a camera 
lens dukakis spokeswoman elizabeth bartle said 
although koppel has interviewed some subjects in person before 
his guests are usually in a separate studio listening to the host 
through an earphone and at times viewing koppel on a monitor 
dukakis campaign officials say this session will be conducted 
with the two men sitting side by side in an 11th floor suite in the 
hyatt regency tech center in denver where the candidate will have 
been campaigning 
the governor agreed earlier this month to appear on 
nightline after abc invited dukakis and bush to appear together 
on the program bush turned the offer down saying that two debates 
between the two candidates were sufficient and that he would be 
too busy campaigning 
the nightline interview comes during a spurt of dukakis 
television appearances in recent days he appeared on abcs good 
morning america and cbss this morning last friday was on 
cnns larry king live monday night with his wife kitty in an 
interview taped sunday and mrs dukakis appeared sunday on cbss 
face the nation 
its an opportunity for the governor to speak directly to as 
many american citizens as he can reach ms bartle said 
dukakis and his aides are banking on the candidate handling 
himself well with koppel one of televisions most respected 
interviewers and on news of his performance reaching more than the 
late night shows 7 million viewers 
hell get an opportunity to dominate the network news not only 
tuesday night but wednesday when he should be able to control the 
sound bites said michael j robinson an associate professor of 
government at georgetown university who has studied the 
relationships between the press and politicians 
with the live interview being broadcast at 1130 pm edt a 
large portion of the viewers staying up to watch will be 
politically active or involved people and very few of them will be 
those undecided voters dukakis needs to win over robinson said 
yet even among the politically involved there will be a value to 
dukakis appearance 
hell persuade people who follow him that its not over 
robinson said hell make an impassioned appeal to his own 
supporters to really work the next two weeks 
penn kimball professor emeritus in journalism at columbia 
universitys graduate school of journalism agrees with robinsons 
evaluation 
kimball said nightline is a fantastic wordofmouth 
program that people seem to talk about the next day 
its the bounce off the program that counts kimball said 
its what the media says happened in the koppel interview that 
will be in all the papers and the evening programs those bounces 
are the ones that will reach the broader audience 
bush campaign spokesman mark goodin said there was no chance 
that the vice president would change his mind and appear on the 
program 
weve done nightline already he said 
bush appeared on the program on a live hookup from houston 
after he won the gop presidential nomination when dukakis agreed 
to appear on the show shortly afterward he sought a facetoface 
interview but was turned down the programs producers felt it 
would be fairer to conduct the questioning the same way bush had 
done it said nightline spokeswoman laura wessner 
the networks invitations to appear on tonights show made it 
clear that the format for the interview was negotiable wessner 
said 
