<TEXT>
mario tapia an associated press photographer 
was in the nicaraguan town of bluefields when hurricane joan hit on 
saturday this is his story 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
you closed your eyes and then you 
opened them again and the city was gone 
bluefields had been observing its 85th birthday and despite the 
hurricane warnings the bars in this caribbean coastal city were 
still full friday afternoon 
few believed how bad it would be even after president daniel 
ortega flew in and toured all the neighborhoods telling people to 
leave 
in the evening the clouds got very thick but the air was still 
and the bay was calm 
the wind came up around 9 pm then came the rain people began 
to leave the low ground near the bay and take refuge in the hotel 
caribe a solid concrete building where i was staying with several 
other journalists and a very good cook 
we had him make us a big meal of lobster and shrimp because we 
thought we might not get much to eat for awhile someone asked for 
wine but there wasnt any 
as the wind rose we didnt want to open the doors of the hotel 
because the wind was so strong we had trouble closing them again 
we took paintings off the walls tore them apart and nailed the 
wood from the frames over the windows 
the refugees stayed calm except for a few children who were 
frightened by the sound of debris hitting the walls and the 
deafening whistle of the wind 
we peered out small windows and keyholes we saw whole zinc 
roofs being tossed off houses and sent clattering down the street 
trees were being ripped apart electric wires were falling 
a cuban weather technician told me that at 3 am saturday at 
the height of the storm the wind gusts hit 145 mph 
after dawn the storm began to ease people began to emerge and 
look around every street was filled with debris every building 
was damaged only a few still had their roofs there were all kinds 
of small dead animals around parrots bats huge rats dogs 
people were just dazed running around going nowhere 
authorities told us there were just 21 dead in the area i couldnt 
believe anybody had survived its a city of 38000 i dont know 
where everybody was hiding 
there were people who had been cut had taken blows one 
17yearold boy had a deep head wound at an openair hospital 
cuban doctors were stitching people up without anesthetic 
the moravian church was crushed it looked like a giant had put 
his foot on it at the market near the docks there were boats 
inside the houses a statue in the city park was decapitated 
the city may have been saved from hurricane joan by its bay 
which protected it from the huge waves and tremendous storm surge 
that is usually the most serious killer in hurricanes 
people shared their food they were very generous there was a 
short period of plenty because all the refrigerators had lost 
power so they wanted to eat right away 
i saw some men carrying a cows hindquarters through the 
streets other people ate downed coconuts in a wrecked seminary a 
man guarded his flock of wet chickens 
people began to make juryrigged roofs out of pieces of zinc in 
the center of town where most stores are owned by chinese 
immigrants the merchants were trying to shelter their remaining 
goods 
prison inmates may have suffered least because the jail was 
solid but then they were taken out with soldiers guarding them 
to work on clearing the road to the airport 
there was no way to get out of town theres no road west 
through the jungle and the airport was closed the only 
communication was by government radio 
the airport finally opened after noon sunday after we took off 
to fly to managua the pilot gave us an aerial tour not one tree 
in bluefields had any leaves the palm trees looked like spikes 
in the park that had been so gay during the anniversary 
celebration the trees looked like skeletons the city practically 
died on its 85th birthday 
then we flew over the port of el bluff on the other side of the 
bay it had been flattened it looked like a bulldozer had scraped 
the earth 
i lived through the earthquake that killed 10000 people in 
managua in 1972 it was deadly but it left houses still standing 
and the leaves on the trees but in bluefields nothing was left 
neither the leaves nor the houses 
how do i feel good because im alive 
</TEXT>
