supreme court justice sandra day oconnor was 
reported in good condition monday at georgetown university hospital 
recovering from surgery for breast cancer 
but while officials at the hospital and the court said the 
58yearold justices condition was good they would not provide 
any details about the nature of her surgery which took place 
friday or her postoperative treatment normally breast cancer 
patients receive some treatment such as chemotherapy or radiation 
to prevent a recurrence 
the los angeles times reported saturday that oconnor underwent 
a mastectomy removal of the breast rather than removal of just a 
malignant tumor called a lumpectomy 
dr christine berg a cancer specialist at georgetown university 
medical school told the newspaper she was familiar with the case 
and that oconnor had a mastectomy 
her tumor was more extensive than could be handled by a 
lumpectomy alone dr berg was quoted as saying 
dr berg who did not take part in performing the surgery told 
the associated press on monday she could not confirm that the 
operation was a mastectomy im not 100 percent certain she 
said 
the hospital also declined to say whether lymph nodes were 
removed from under oconnors arm in the surgery and what test 
results if any from the nodes were available 
the national cancer institute says the fiveyear survival rate 
for breast cancer patients whose cancer is confined to the breast 
is greater than 85 percent if the cancer has spread to the lymph 
nodes the survival rate drops to 70 percent or less 
dr robert s siegel director of cancer treatment at george 
washington university hospital said in an interview that typically 
the lymph glands are removed whether the patient undergoes a 
mastectomy or lumpectomy 
oconnor released an earlier statement that said she intends to 
be back at the supreme court on oct 31 when the justices return 
from a twoweek recess to resume hearing oral arguments 
she already was doing some work from her hospital room 
she issued an order monday temporarily shielding goodyear tire amp 
rubber co from having to pay a 4 million damage award to a 
minnesota service station attendant injured by an exploding tire 
oconnor granted an emergency request by goodyear to extend a 
lower court order permitting the company to withhold the money 
pending action by the full supreme court on a formal goodyear 
appeal 
