<TEXT>
a national labor relations board judge on 
monday overruled harvard universitys objection to a union election 
in may accusing the university of misrepresenting both the unions 
conduct and labor law 
in a harshly worded opinion nlrb administrative law judge joel 
a harmatz certified the harvard union of clerical and technical 
workers as the winner in the election to unionize harvards 3400 
technical and clerical workers 
the union an affiliate of the 1 millionmember american 
federation of state county and municipal employees won the 
election on a 15301486 vote characterized by a 90 percent 
turnout among those eligible 
harmatz dismissed as unfounded harvards complaints that the 
union illegally coerced yes votes through a coordinated 
campaign to assure that union supporters cast ballots 
harvards brief in the case harmatz said is replete with 
misinterpretations of the record of eight days of hearings the 
nlrb held in august on the universitys charges 
because these references either are not supported by or 
grossly overstate the proven facts this decision seeks to at this 
level bring a halt to this approach the judge said 
he further chastised harvard saying additional delay has 
been occasioned by the employers proclivity to disguise as fact 
argumentative and sometimes frivolous interpretations of the 
evidence in the case 
the union drive which began in 1975 and the universitys 
challenge had been viewed by several labor leaders as a major test 
of their ability to organize new cadres of educated white and 
graycollar technical workers assuming a greater proportion of the 
workforce 
harvard spokeswoman marjorie heffron said no decision has been 
made on whether to appeal harmatzs ruling to the full fivemember 
board under the law it has two weeks to file an appeal 
