<TEXT>
soviet icebreakers trying to help rescue two 
whales off barrow alaska also were involved in a whale rescue off 
eastern siberia three years ago an american official involved in 
joint ussoviet ocean research said monday 
in 1985 soviet icebreakers broke through an ice barrier in the 
gulf of anadyr trying to free several dozen beluga whales said 
robert v miller deputy director of the national marine laboratory 
in seattle 
reports are mixed but i think they did get some out miller 
said in a telephone interview 
unlike the barrow whales trapped under the ice the anadyr 
whales were in a small area of water that was cut off from the 
ocean by a ring of ice icebreakers had to break through the ring 
belugas are smaller than the california gray whales off barrow 
typically 15 feet long compared with 50 feet 
miller said he did not know whether the soviet vessels involved 
in the barrow attempt were also involved at anadyr 
the gulf of anadyr is in the western bering sea south of the 
chukchi peninsula the easternmost portion of siberia 
the united states and the soviet union have been cooperating on 
whale and other marine mammal research in the northern pacific 
bering sea and arctic oceans since 1973 under the ussoviet 
treaty on environmental protection 
they have conducted at least 15 joint research cruises and 
scientists from the two countries visit each others laboratories 
about twice a year miller said 
though the icebreakers at barrow were not part of the research 
agreement the willingness of the soviet union to lend a hand shows 
that its scientists are very much interested in marine mammals 
and conservation of these animals miller said 
