central america remains the exception to 
worldwide peace trends and foreign aid to rebels subverts the 
regional peace process secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar 
said monday 
at this juncture when other conflicts seem to be on the way 
to solution i appeal to the central american countries and other 
countries to renew their collective commitment to peace perez de 
cuellar said in his annual report on the region 
central american governments must redouble efforts to overcome 
obstacles and the countries outside the region with ties and 
interests in it must resolutely decide to facilitate that task and 
refrain from any action likely to undermine it he said without 
naming countries 
the united states supports rebels battling nicaraguas 
sandinista government cuba and the soviet union back leftwing 
guerrillas in el salvador and other countries 
perez de cuellar was commenting on the peace agreement signed 
aug 7 1987 by the presidents of costa rica guatemala 
nicaragua honduras and el salvador it calls for progress toward 
democracy and national reconciliation noninterference in the 
internal affairs of other countries and an end to foreign military 
aid 
there has been an apparent lack of similar progress towards 
fulfillment of the commitments on nonuse of territory to attack 
other states and on termination of aid for irregular forces and 
insurrectionist movements perez de cuellar said 
the lack of progress has undermined the strategy aimed at 
bringing about the cessation of hostilities on the basis of a broad 
amnesty and democratization in conjunction with the termination of 
aid for rebels he added 
significant progress in democratic reforms was made 
immediately after the agreement was signed perez de cuellar said 
he cited establishment of national reconciliation commissions 
amnesty decrees the lifting of states of emergency expanding 
political pluralism and movements toward ending hostilities 
now however the principle of simultaneous democratization and 
ending aid to rebels appears to have been replaced by the 
principle of unilateralism he said and reciprocity must be 
restored 
central americas development has been hurt by the political 
turmoil and the crisis is perpetuating unjust social and economic 
structures perez de cuellar declared 
