<TEXT>
an ancient stone carving that thailand said was 
stolen from its country will be returned by the art institute of 
chicago in an effort to end the ongoing dispute the institute said 
monday 
the lintel will be returned in exchange for an artifact of 
equal artistic merit to be donated by the chicagobased elizabeth 
f cheney foundation a philanthropic group that wanted to help 
resolve the dispute said institute spokeswoman virginia voedisch 
the museum has maintained that it obtained the lintel 
legitimately as a donation from a private foundation and had 
refused thailands demands that it be returned 
but protesters who say the artwork is the thai equivalent of 
the statue of liberty torch have demanded its return negotiations 
between the museum and thai officials broke off in july ms 
voedisch said 
the elizabeth f cheney foundation and the art institute in a 
desire to resolve the stalemate in negotiations and maintain the 
positive relationship that existed between thailand and the united 
states has erected a solution ms voedisch said 
upon receipt of this gift the art institute will relinquish 
all rights and title to the lintel and donate it to thailand the 
museum said in a statement 
ms voedisch said a decision was expected soon on a replacement 
for the lintel and that the lintel would be returned at that time 
the museum and the foundation are considering several works but 
no decision on a replacement for the lintel has been made she said 
she said thai officials had been alerted of the museums 
decision but she did not think a response had been received by the 
art institute 
the lintel a 2by3 foot stone crosspiece designed to fit above 
a door or window depicts in relief the hindu god vishnu reclining 
on water it dates to cambodias khmer dynasty covering the years 
8051250 
it disappeared from the phnom rung temple a national monument 
in northeastern thailand during the 1960s thai officials say 
in february 1988 21 years after the lintel was first displayed 
at the art institute the museum learned that the thai government 
wanted it returned for the temples restoration the museum said 
negotiations between thai officials and the art institute began 
at that time 
thai demonstrators protested outside the museum earlier this 
year trying to have it returned in time for reopening ceremonies 
at the thai temple in may 
the art institute received the lintel from the chicagobased 
alsdorf foundation which acquired it in 1967 through a new york 
art dealer the museum said 
the new york dealer in turn purchased the carving in 1966 from a 
dealer in bangkok where it was being offered for sale on the open 
market the art institute said 
