the captain of an italian freighter that 
collided with a greek cruise ship and left two people dead and two 
others missing appeared in court monday on manslaughter charges and 
said he was not to blame for the accident 
capt flavio caminale of genoa italy was arrested friday 
after his freighter adige hit and sank a greek cruise ship carrying 
486 british students and their teachers 
two greek seamen were killed and more than 60 people were 
injured before the 6300ton cruise ship jupiter went down less 
than one mile off piraeus harbor near athens two british 
passengers vivienne barley 14 and bernard butt 41 were 
missing and presumed dead the merchant marine ministry said 
caminale 45 is charged with manslaughter through negligence 
causing serious injuries causing a shipwreck and ignoring shipping 
regulations 
im innocent caminale said during the 30minute hearing 
i was not technically responsible for this tragedy and am very 
sorry about the death of these people a weeping caminale said 
outside court 
district attorney antonis roussos and investigating magistrate 
telemachus flezouras ordered the captain detained pending a court 
appearance wednesday in which he will be questioned and the charges 
formally recorded 
under greek judicial procedure a defendant must be presented 
with the charges in a court the next working day after his arrest 
in a subsequent hearing he is questioned at length and the 
magistrate revises the charges if necessary before formalizing them 
the magistrate will decide wednesday whether caminale will be 
jailed pending trial if convicted of the charges caminale could 
spend one to five years in prison 
the 5500ton adige was sailing into piraeus with a cargo of 
automobiles when it punched a hole in the side of the jupiter 
which was taking the british children and their teachers on an 
eightday mediterranean cruise the children jumped overboard and 
were picked up by tugboats and fishing vessels before the jupiter 
sank 40 minutes later 
two jupiter crewmen died when they were crushed against the 
ships side as they tried to attach cables from a tugboat 
more than 60 passengers were hospitalized most suffering from 
shock and minor injuries all but one have returned to britain 
none of the adiges 22member crew was injured and the vessel 
suffered only minor damage 
greek and italian accounts of the collision differ sharply 
