<TEXT>
some offerings in the brooklyn academy of 
musics annual next wave festival are avantgarde and some reach 
for the far out 
the warrior ant opening production of the sixth season is 
one of the latter there is an audience for big elaborate stage 
devices rockconcertloud music and general oddness this is the 
audience which also must be able to swallow large helpings of 
muddle and pretentiousness for the warrior ant 
the threehour show already seen at the spoleto festival in 
charleston in philadelphia and at yale university opened sunday 
night at the brooklyn academys majestic theater 
act 1 is like a mardi gras it starts with a metal toy ant 
scooting out onto the stage a narrator in a periwig says on the 
sixth day there was created crawling things and it was good he 
goes on to explain that ants are conceived on one night of the 
year known as funky tuesday and that like bees drones die and 
queens live 
most of this long act is very busy with floats atop small cars 
choreographed break dancers steeldrum bands and amplified 
caribbeanstyle singing with the words not understood lengthy 
narration intended as an epic poem is vacuous with pretentious 
literary wording usually ending in a now zinger such as 
he blew me away 
a tall metal ant standing upright legs waving is wheeled on 
for the finale from its innards comes a japanese doll the title 
character 
in act 2 the ant and a worm manipulated by bunraku puppeteers 
yoshida tamamatsu and kanju kiritake and five assistants go 
through the path of least resistance in a forgotten circle of 
hell where artists reside steel drummers and a string quartet 
provide accompaniment for this and some bellydancing after a few 
snipes via a narrator at artists the ant finds his father a 
termite and they have an existentialist conversation thats fairly 
hard to follow 
in act 3 the ant falls in love with a death moth there are 
songs and narration which here becomes so flowery and rococo it is 
funny 
the warrior ant is the first time the osaka japan bunraku 
puppet theater has collaborated on a western project development 
of the play began in 1984 lee breuer liza lorwin and bob telson 
who developed the gospel at colonus which told the oedipus 
story in gospel music and drew parallels with jesus produced 
breuer directed in brooklyn mabou mines in a coproducer they 
