<TEXT>
upward pressure on rents is likely to occur in 
the near future and if that is so you may expect a rise in demands 
for rent controls 
one without the other has been rare in recent years and nothing 
seems likely to change that relationship some people will always 
be for rent control and others will oppose it seldom can they 
speak civilly to each other 
the usual fireworks may be expected therefore as pressure 
builds on the rental market a consequence of reduced tax benefits 
for owners and builders and a proliferation of local restrictions 
on new construction 
recognizing the emerging situation the nonprofit 
independentminded urban land institute commissioned an 
evaluation by anthony downs a senior fellow at the brookings 
institution he comes down hard against controls 
downs contends in his recently released volume that controls 
inhibit new rental construction cause existing units to 
deteriorate faster and actually impose disadvantages on those who 
are thought to benefit 
it is a conventional finding and it is likely to be treated 
conventionally by those opposed philosophically or morally to 
freemarket rents 
its impact is likely to be diminished even further be its 
sponsorhip which includes the national multi housing council the 
building owners and managers association international and the 
national association of realtors 
nevertheless it has much to say about the subject that is 
worthwhile especially in view of the likelihood that reductions in 
rental construction plus a tendency toward rent inflation will 
resurrect the debate 
though the subject lies dormant now there are more than 200 
communities with some form of residential rent controls most 
adopted during periods of rapid general inflation in the 1970s and 
most in the northeast and california 
do they work for some and for a limited time it seems but 
downs contends that in the long run they impose two major 
disadvantages upon those who are supposed to be the major 
beneficiaries lowincome households 
first he says controls increase rather than decrease the 
discretionary power of owners by intensifying tenant competition 
for vacant units 
says downs owners then tend to choose higherincome tenants 
over poor ones since the former pose less risk owners also 
discriminate against tenants on the basis of race ethnicity age 
and number of children 
then he contends controls may increase homelessness by 
reducing the available supply of rental housing and thus the 
access of the poor to that supply 
these contentions are likely to play a big role in the arguments 
to come because already there is a serious shortage of lowincome 
housing 
according to downs in 1983 the number of renter households for 
whom 250 or less represented 30 percent of income was 12 million 
at the same time the number of units priced at 250 or less per 
month was 875 million 
harsh as that reality was it has grown worse since then says 
downs and that brings up the question of how to handle the 
problem by imposing rent controls to temporarily assist while 
worsening the longterm problem or by allowing freemarket rents 
which eventually bring more units on market 
philosophically there is probably no meeting ground for those 
at the extremes of this argument no more than there is a common 
interest regarding another aspect of the subject ie the fate of 
landlords 
rent controls obviously impose economic losses upon the owners 
of rental housing units penalties that no other participants in 
the economic community are expected to accept 
owners of controlled units for instance may be forced to take 
operating expenses from their own pockets in effect denying their 
own families the market value of the property declines their 
investment can even be wiped out 
landlords legitimately ask therefore if attempts at fair play 
for one member of society should arbitarily be at the expense of 
another rather than of the total community 
</TEXT>
