for the actress spoils of war represents nearly a yearlong 
journey to broadway nelligan has lived with the character and the 
play since last january when the director austin pendleton 
suggested her for the role of elise 
the play was presented to me then as an unfinished piece of 
work says the canadianborn actress the first act was pretty 
much in shape and the second act wasnt there was a beginning and 
an end but i didnt say what are you going to do with it i 
said i want to do it 
about two weeks before rehearsals started nelligan sat down for 
a threehour meeting with weller to talk not about the play but 
about the woman in it they discussed who she was as well as 
things the playwright knew about elise from his own life 
it was the first time in her 16 years as a professional actress 
that nelligan was there during the creation 
ive worked on new plays with writers but ive never worked 
on a play that came such a long way the actress says michael 
was finding the play as we went along 
the character of elise started out as an auntie mame she was 
just a real goodtime girl in the first performance she appeared 
as a ghost to a character who is no longer even in the play the 
adult martin who is on the point of divorcing his wife 
weller rewrote the play several times before the drama opened in 
may at the tiny offbroadway second stage the theater company was 
devoting its entire season to the playwright and spoils of war 
was the finale in a year that also saw productions of wellers 
moonchildren and loose ends 
the rewriting continued during the plays second stage 
engagement often with the actors rehearsing one version during the 
day and performing a different one at night 
it was an awful period nelligan admits particularly until 
the actors discovered the people they were playing all they could 
do was trust the playwright she recalls 
i thought michael was moving toward something but it was just 
very painful to be performing something when i didnt know what i 
was doing a lot of time nelligan says ive always been sure 
of my lines and now i wasnt sure what would come out of my mouth 
because the lines were always being changed 
there were other changes after the offbroadway run ended and 
the company prepared for its november opening at new yorks music 
box theater 
there was a break from the end of june until the middle of 
august while weller worked on a new ending 
there are a couple of new actors a new set and more 
rewrites nelligan says 
one thing nelligan didnt discuss with weller was what he was 
going to do with the play 
id never ask him that the actress says i think thats 
the way he likes to work its his play it isnt mine 
nelligan insists the role was not tailormade for her 
michael was writing from memory she says but its been 
useful to see all the places he has gone to with the play because 
that informs what you end up with even all the rejected 
possibilities that he explored they might be taken out but they 
are in your memory to use for whats left 
it was nelligans idea to let her character sport long red hair 
and she willingly donned a wig to make elise more flamboyant and 
fun 
the character has got quite a range bigger than anybody i 
ever played nelligan says she can have a lot of fun and gives 
people a lot of fun and then shes also in a lot of pain and a lot 
of trouble shes a human fleshandblood creature 
although born in canada nelligan didnt make her professional 
canadian debut until spoils of war opened in toronto in 
september before coming to new york 
most of her career has been centered in england and the united 
states despite her schooling at londons central school of speech 
and drama her best training she says has been has been watching 
other performers particularly at the national theater and the 
royal shakespeare company 
the greatest teacher i ever had was an actor named colin 
blakeley who died last year nelligan says i did george 
bernard shaws heartbreak house with him when i was 24 years old 
and i learned a lot 
nothing she had done prepared her for the intense exhilarating 
work of spoils of war particularly in its early days 
the process had been so overheated what with all the rewrites 
the short short rehearsal time and that tiny theater at second 
stage and no money nelligan says getting it on stage and 
having it survive all those things was hard 
i was so tired she remembers then after a few weeks it 
got to be something i could do and go away from 
</TEXT>
