grain and soybean futures were moderately lower 
in early trading today on the chicago board of trade reflecting 
disappointment over slack export business and improved growing 
conditions in south america 
the soybean market appeared to be leading the grain markets 
lower on reports of fairly heavy weekend showers in brazil and 
forecasts for more rain by midweek in both brazil and argentina 
analysts said 
the generally slow pace of grain export sales continued to exert 
pressure on corn and wheat prices 
an increase in exports is what we need in both markets to get 
things rolling said dale gustafson an analyst with drexel 
burnham lambert inc in chicago 
he said the corn market remained nervous about the effect on 
export demand of aflatoxin a naturallyoccurring cancercausing 
substance that has turned up in some newly harvested corn 
at least one ship had to unload corn bound for overseas after 
federal inspectors found aflatoxin in the shipment and japan is 
weighing restrictions on us corn contaminated by aflatoxin 
in early trading wheat was 1 cents to 4 cents lower with the 
contract for delivery in december at 415 a bushel corn was 
cent to 2 cents lower with december at 281 a bushel oats were 
1 cents to 3 cents lower with december at 247 a bushel 
soybeans were cent to 6 cents lower with november at 769 a 
bushel 
cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures were mostly 
lower in early trading on the chicago mercantile exchange 
