<TEXT>
mcorp a financial services organization said 
monday it lost 517 million in the third quarter and that its board 
had placed a moratorium on payment of its outstanding debt and 
preferred stock dividends 
the loss reflects a substantial addition to the allowance for 
possible loan losses a large provision for possible losses on 
assets acquired upon foreclosure and other costs associated with 
asset quality pressures the company reported 
the moratorium included payment of principal and interest on all 
parent company publicly and privately placed indebtedness for 
borrowed money 
the moratorium which affects approximately 470 million in 
outstanding debt was effective oct 21 and will remain in place 
indefinitely officials said 
the moratorium permits mcorp to marshal it assets in its 
recapitalization proposal pending before the federal deposit 
insurance corp 
the loss for the quarter ended sept 30 compares with a net loss 
of 737 million for the same period in 1987 
the company had net income of 462 million for the second 
quarter of 1988 including a 215 million gain from sale of its 80 
percent interest in mtech 
as a result of the loss officials said that obligations under 
certain debt covenants prohibit mcorp from declaring dividends 
unless it returns to profitability or obtains waivers from 
bankholders 
the moratorium does not affect the companys mbanks or 
customers said gene h bishop mcorp chairman and chief 
executive officer business will continue as usual 
he said the boards action was designed to conserve maximum 
resources at the parent company so that they can be used in 
connection with the recapitalization of the company and its banking 
subsidiaries 
separately mcorp officials said the board of governors of the 
federal reserve system had issued a temporary order directing the 
company not to declare dividends on its common or preferred shares 
or otherwise engage in any transaction that could result in the 
dissipation of assets of the parent company without the approval of 
the federal reserve 
the decision to suspend payments of dividends and to declare the 
debt moratorium did not result from the federal reserve order 
company officials said and mcorp is in compliance with the order 
</TEXT>
